A group of queer activists illegally occupying a mansion in Camps Bay in Cape Town for over a week, have been ordered to leave by 8 October. Nobesuthu Hejana shares the details. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - A group of seven queer activists have until midday on Thursday to vacate the premises of a Camps Bay mansion in Cape Town. The Western Cape High Court ruled against the group, called the Queer Radical Feminist Activist Collective, after an urgent application by a company managing the property and the homeowner. READ: Activist group occupies Camps Bay mansion The group unlawfully occupied the mansion to highlight discrimination against the Queer community, lack of land, and gender-based violence. The City of Cape Town is promising to provide alternative shelter, if they qualify, after three members of the group said they would be homeless if immediately evicted.